    p.title Strangers on a Train
    p.sub Alfred Hitchcock, 1951
    img(data-src='#{path}/strangers_on_a_train.png')
    p.date 24 April 2020
    p.description loved the tennis match as an element of suspense. Camera mvmts during this scene were great, and got increasingly erratic which really drove the movie toward its climax at the crazy carousel scene: a mirroring of the first scene of the film with the fast moving train, but like a twisted psychotic version, with the spinning.
    //- p.description rly thrilling
    //- patricia highsmith novel! and Farley Granger is a true beau
    //- tennis match as an element of suspense...nice. Camera mvmts during this scene were great, got increasingly erratic
    //- crazy carousel as climax confrontation scene was great aand clever ttouch as well. Invoked the beginning scene with fast moving train, but like a twisted psychotic version, with the spinning.

  

  div.movie
    p.title Gone with the Wind
    p.sub Victor Fleming, 1939
    img(data-src='#{path}/gone_with_the_wind.png')
    p.date 22 April 2020
    p.description.
      After all, tomorrow is another day!!!!
      <br><br>
      Reactions:
      <br>
      - I can't believe this was in made in color??
      <br>
      - Clark Gable is not handsome at all, and all of his character's love scenes made me uncomfortable, they were so aggressive and almost all non-consensual. Leslie Howard as Ashley Wilkes though was alright--overall, a darling.
      <br>
      - I appreciate the outright selfishness of Scarlett O'Hara (Vivien Leigh), and how slight her character growth was LOL
      <br>
      - Melly Hamilton (Olivia de Havlland) was definitely the best
      <br>
      - This is the 1940's interpretation of the 1860's, what does this even mean for me watching in 2020? It's impossible to say.
      <br> 
      - Icky racial politics in this one, but has come some ways from <i>The Birth of a Nation</i>
      <br>
      - Too long, clearly, but still entertaining. I was engaged the whole time, and by the time it was over it felt definitely deserving of the term "epic"

